<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C6CFF87FF71FA73FC90F06D" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF71FA73FD6AF05D" blockId="10.[166,644,1519,1546]" box="[166,644,1519,1546]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
<heading id="6F6881EC6C6CFF87FF71FA73FD6AF05D" box="[166,644,1519,1546]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="F39F4D036C6CFF87FF71FA73FD6AF05D" authority="(Hubner, [1803])" baseAuthorityName="Hubner" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[166,644,1519,1546]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cryphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraudatricula">
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C6CFF87FF71FA73FE5DF05D" bold="true" box="[166,435,1519,1546]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">Cryphia fraudatricula</emphasis>
(Hübner, [1803])
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CF983FC90F06D" blockId="10.[166,1225,1567,1786]" box="[219,894,1567,1594]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FDA0F983FD1EF06D" box="[631,752,1567,1594]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[170,203,1708,1730]" captionTargetBox="[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-8@8.[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 37–42. Eggs of Condicinae: 37–38 — Eucarta amethystina; eggs of Bryophilinae: 39–42 — Cryphia fraudatricula. Scale bars: 39–41 — 100 µm; 37–38, 42 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453306/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 39–41</figureCitation>
). Egg white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C6CFF87FF0CF9A3FD9BF17D" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CF9A3FE59F0AD" blockId="10.[166,1225,1567,1786]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
Chorion not ridged. Micropylar area represented by rosette and 1 row indistinct, long, narrow and pointed cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FDFFF9C3FD97F02D" box="[552,633,1631,1658]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[170,203,1708,1730]" captionTargetBox="[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-8@8.[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 37–42. Eggs of Condicinae: 37–38 — Eucarta amethystina; eggs of Bryophilinae: 39–42 — Cryphia fraudatricula. Scale bars: 39–41 — 100 µm; 37–38, 42 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453306/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 42</figureCitation>
). Rosette very elevated with 12–13 long and narrow cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FEC9F9E3FE77F0CD" box="[286,409,1663,1690]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetId="figure-74@9.[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 43–48. Eggs of Bryophilinae, Cryphia fraudatricula: 43–45 — micropylar area; 46 — sculpture of egg chorion; 47 — each of tubercles is surrounded by same 6–7 tubercles; 48 — single tubercle. Scale bars 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453308/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 43–44</figureCitation>
). Walls of rosette cells flat and strongly elevated, especially in middle part (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FF32F903FEDCF0ED" box="[229,306,1695,1722]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetId="figure-74@9.[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 43–48. Eggs of Bryophilinae, Cryphia fraudatricula: 43–45 — micropylar area; 46 — sculpture of egg chorion; 47 — each of tubercles is surrounded by same 6–7 tubercles; 48 — single tubercle. Scale bars 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453308/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Sculpture starry, very typical (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FD73F903FD1CF0ED" box="[676,754,1695,1722]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetId="figure-74@9.[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 43–48. Eggs of Bryophilinae, Cryphia fraudatricula: 43–45 — micropylar area; 46 — sculpture of egg chorion; 47 — each of tubercles is surrounded by same 6–7 tubercles; 48 — single tubercle. Scale bars 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453308/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 46</figureCitation>
). Pattern looks like high, narrow-angled tubercles, each of which urrounded by same 6–7 tubercles. All tubercles interconnected by bent edges (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FEE6F943FE44F0AD" box="[305,426,1759,1786]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[174,207,1706,1728]" captionTargetBox="[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetId="figure-74@9.[174,1225,195,1682]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 43–48. Eggs of Bryophilinae, Cryphia fraudatricula: 43–45 — micropylar area; 46 — sculpture of egg chorion; 47 — each of tubercles is surrounded by same 6–7 tubercles; 48 — single tubercle. Scale bars 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453308/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 47–48</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CF893FD9BF17D" blockId="10.[219,629,1807,1834]" box="[219,629,1807,1834]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">O v i p o s i t i o n. Eggs solitary laid.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
